Caption: Figure 4: The drag force on a rotating cylinder inside the wind tunnel with Reynolds number R = 1,000, and ω = 0.1. The parallel-to-the-wind component of the drag force (a) shows the same behavior as before, in the case of fixed cylinder. During the transient stage, the transverse-to-the-wind component of the force (b) also increases, reaches a maximum, and decreases. However, this component does not stabilize. Instead, it oscillates around a mean value. The oscillation is due to the alternate formation of counterclockwise and clockwise vortices, being a signature of the von Kármán street. For small values of R, up to a few dozens, both components of the drag force don’t oscillate, a signature of the absence of successive vortices.
